<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-05-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-05-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="535" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d535">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Swenson</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-05-01"><hi rend="italic">May 1,
                                1900</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 95.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            dispatch No. 160, of March 29 last, reporting the action of the Danish
                            Government in banishing two American citizens from Denmark on the ground
                            that they are Mormon missionaries.</p>
                        <p>In reply I have to inform you that the Department fully approves your
                            course in regard to the matter and has nothing to add to its instruction
                            to Mr. Risley of July 23, 1897 (<ref target="frus1897#pg_123">Foreign
                                Relations 1897, p. 123</ref>), which shows the present attitude of
                            this Government toward Mormon missionaries.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>